snippet.textDisplay: This, folks, is called the "free market."  Matt Colvin is not evil. He did nothing wrong. He did not break the law (to the best of my knowledge). He saw there was going to be a surge in demand for a resource, did the work to collect the resource, and then tried to sell it for the price he thought people would pay. If they didn't want it at that price, he would have had to drop the price to sell. Instead, in the end, he donated the whole thing to the public health authorities, the government (which has all the resources you pay for with your taxes) to avoid a flood of death threats. And it was all unnecessary. Hand sanitizer will not save you. Twenty thousand bottles is nothing in the interstate market. NOTHING. Wash your hands, people. Use a bit of soap, and rinse thoroughly.  If you had gone out two weeks ago, when all this was getting under way, and bought a case of sanitizer, you would not now think you need to rob this man, at government gun point, in order to supply thoughtless grasshoppers like yourself. Remember: if this can be done to Colvin today, tomorrow The Authorities might decide that some resource you possess is crucial to the Public Good, and come to empty your home, or your bank account. The ultimate emergency resource is yourself, and your liberty. Don't fall for the lie that you must surrender it for the collective good. Tyranny is never a good, not ever, for anybody other than the ones in control, the ones who hoard POWER.

snippet.textDisplay:
Anti price-gouging laws ensure that vital supplies are consumed immediately in an emergency.
In a crisis, it is obvious that supplies of urgently needed goods will be limited, so instead of buying what you need at inflated prices (i.e. just getting 3 or 4 of gallons of gas at $10 per gallon after a hurricane), price-gouging laws encourage you to buy as much of a vital good as you can, even if you don't really need much (or any at all), thus ensuring that stockpiles are immediately wiped out (as we see in this video). Huge profit from inflated prices also ensures increased production/redistribution, and thus a quick end to the shortage.
